      "narration": "Long voyages need ship-to-ship signals, and waving flags is slow, so Nami designs a codebook — and to design it well she first has to measure something slippery: how much information does a message carry? That was Claude Shannon's starting question in nineteen forty-eight, and his answer is that rare equals informative. The message the sun rose carries essentially nothing, because you already knew it; the message snow in the Sahara carries a lot, precisely because it is surprising. The measure is I of x equals minus log-base-two of the probability of x, in bits. A certain event, probability one, carries zero bits — no surprise. A fifty-fifty event carries one bit. An event with probability one-over-one-thousand-twenty-four carries ten bits. Now, why the logarithm, of all functions? Because we want independent surprises to add. Two independent events with probabilities p and q have joint probability p-times-q, and minus the log of p-times-q equals minus log-p minus log-q — so the log is the unique choice that turns multiplication of probabilities into addition of information, which is exactly the additive behavior we want from a measure of surprise. And the word bit here is not a metaphor: an event with probability one-eighth carries three bits because identifying it takes exactly three optimal yes-or-no questions, each halving the possibilities — eight to four to two to one. Information is surprise, measured in the number of yes-or-no questions the answer is worth.",
